<exercise label="Library__272__setStewart15_4__problem_6__pg" xml:id="int-polar31">
    <webwork source="Library/272/setStewart15_4/problem_6.pg"/>
</exercise> 
   

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the iterated integral <m>I = \int_{-3}^{0} \int_{-\sqrt{9-y^2}}^{0} \frac{y}{x^2 + y^2+1} \, dx \, dy.</m>
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Sketch (and label) the region of integration.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Convert the given iterated integral to one in polar coordinates.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate the iterated integral in (b).
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  State one possible interpretation of the value you found in (c).
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The region <m>R</m> defined by <m>-\sqrt{9-y^2} \leq x \leq 0</m> and
                <m>-3 \leq y \leq 0</m> is the portion of the circle centered at the origin of radius 3 that is in the third quadrant.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <md>
                  \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \int_{0}^{3} \frac{r\sin(\theta)}{r^2+1} r \, dr \, d\theta
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m> \arctan(3)-3</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>f(x,y) = \frac{y}{x^2 + y^2+1}</m> is the density of the lamina defined by <m>R</m>,
                then <m>I</m> represents the mass of the lamina.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The region <m>R</m> defined by <m>-\sqrt{9-y^2} \leq x \leq 0</m> and
                <m>-3 \leq y \leq 0</m> is the portion of the circle centered at the origin of radius 3 that is in the third quadrant.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The region <m>R</m> is described in polar coordinates by
                <m>0 \leq r \leq 3</m> and <m>\pi \leq \theta \leq \frac{3 \pi}{2}</m>.
                With <m>r^2=x^2+y^2</m> and <m>y = r\sin(\theta)</m> we have
                <md>
                  \int_{-3}^{0} \int_{-\sqrt{9-y^2}}^{0} \frac{y}{x^2 + y^2+1} \, dx \, dy = \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \int_{0}^{3} \frac{r\sin(\theta)}{r^2+1} r \, dr \, d\theta
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Dividing <m>1+r^2</m> into <m>r^2</m> shows that <m>\frac{r^2}{r^2+1} = 1 - \frac{1}{r^2+1}</m>.
                Using this fact gives us
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \int_{0}^{3} \frac{r^2\sin(\theta)}{r^2+1} \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \sin(\theta) \int_{0}^{3} \frac{r^2}{r^2+1} \, dr \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \sin(\theta) \int_{0}^{3} 1-\frac{1}{r^2+1} \, dr \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \sin(\theta)  \left(r-\arctan(r)\right)\mid_{0}^{3} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \sin(\theta)  \left(3-\arctan(3)\right) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \left(3-\arctan(3)\right) (-\cos(\theta))\mid_{\pi}^{3\pi/2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \arctan(3)-3</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>f(x,y) = \frac{y}{x^2 + y^2+1}</m> is the density of the lamina defined by <m>R</m>,
                then <m>I</m> represents the mass of the lamina.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        </solution>

        
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>D</m> be the region that lies inside the unit circle in the plane.
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Set up and evaluate an iterated integral in polar coordinates whose value is the area of <m>D</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Determine the exact average value of <m>f(x,y) = y</m> over the upper half of <m>D</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Find the exact center of mass of the lamina over the portion of <m>D</m> that lies in the first quadrant and has its mass density distribution given by <m>\delta(x,y) = 1</m>. (Before making any calculations, where do you expect the center of mass to lie? Why?)
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Find the exact volume of the solid that lies under the surface <m>z = 8-x^2-y^2</m> and over the unit disk, <m>D</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <md>
                  \int_{0}^{2 \pi} \int_{0}^{1} r \, dr \, d\theta = \pi
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m> \frac{2}{3\pi}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The region and density function are symmetric around the line <m>y=x</m>,
                so we should expect the center of mass to lie on this line.
                The center of mass is at point <m>(\frac{2}{3\pi},  \frac{2}{3\pi})</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m> \frac{15 \pi}{2}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The unit disk <m>D</m> is described in polar coordinates as
                <m>0 \leq r \leq 1</m> and <m>0 \leq \theta \leq 2 \pi</m>.
                So an iterated integral in polar coordinates whose value is the area of <m>D</m> is
                <md>
                  \int_{0}^{2 \pi} \int_{0}^{1} r \, dr \, d\theta
                </md>.
                The value of this iterated integral is <m>\pi</m>, which is exactly the area of the unit circle.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The upper half <m>H</m> of <m>D</m> is represented by restricting <m>\theta</m> to <m>0 \leq \theta \leq \pi</m>.
                Since the area of this half-disk is <m>\pi</m>,
                the exact average value of
                <m>f(x,y) = y</m> over the upper half of <m>D</m> is
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{1}{\pi} \iint_H f(x,y) \, dA \amp =  \int_{0}^{\pi} \int_{0}^{1} r (r\sin(\theta)) \, dr \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{\pi} \int_{0}^{\pi} \sin(\theta) \frac{1}{3}r^3\mid_{0}^{1} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{3 \pi} \int_{0}^{\pi} \sin(\theta) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{3 \pi} (-\cos(\theta))\mid_{0}^{\pi}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{3\pi}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The region and density function are symmetric around the line <m>y=x</m>,
                so we should expect the center of mass to lie on this line.
                The inequalities <m>0 \leq \theta \leq \frac{\pi}{2}</m> describe the first quadrant region <m>Q</m> of <m>D</m>.
                The area of <m>Q</m> is <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
                The center of mass <m>(\overline{x}, \overline{y})</m> of this region with mass density distribution given by <m>\delta(x,y) = 1</m> is found by
                <md>
                  <mrow>\overline{x} \amp = \frac{2}{\pi} \int_{0}^{\pi/2} \int_{0}^{1} r(r \cos(\theta)) \, dr \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{\pi} \int_{0}^{\pi/2} \cos(\theta) \frac{1}{3}r^3\mid_{0}^{1} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{3 \pi} \int_{0}^{\pi/2} \cos(\theta) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{3 \pi} (\sin(\theta))\mid_{0}^{\pi/2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{3\pi}</mrow>
                </md>
                and
                <md>
                  <mrow>\overline{y} \amp =  \frac{2}{\pi} \int_{0}^{\pi/2} \int_{0}^{1} r (r\sin(\theta)) \, dr \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{\pi} \int_{0}^{\pi/2} \sin(\theta) \frac{1}{3}r^3\mid_{0}^{1} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{3 \pi} \int_{0}^{\pi/2} \sin(\theta) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{3 \pi} (-\cos(\theta))\mid_{0}^{\pi/2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{3\pi}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The volume is
                <md>
                  <mrow>\iint_D 8-x^2-y^2 \, dA \amp = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \int_0^1 (8-r^2) r \, dr \, d \theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \left( 4r^2 -\frac{1}{4}r^4 \right)\mid_0^1 \, d \theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{15}{4} \int_{0}^{2\pi} \, d \theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{15 \pi}{2}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        </solution>

        
      </exercise>


      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For each of the following iterated integrals, 
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>sketch and label the region of integration, 
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p> convert the integral to the other coordinate system (if given in polar, to rectangular; if given in rectangular, to polar), and 
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                choose one of the two iterated integrals to evaluate exactly.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \int_{0}^{3}  r^3 \, dr \, d\theta</m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\int_{0}^{2} \int_{-\sqrt{1-(x-1)^2}}^{\sqrt{1-(x-1)^2}} \sqrt{x^2 + y^2} \, dy \, dx</m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\int_0^{\pi/2} \int_0^{\sin(\theta)} r \sqrt{1-r^2} \, dr \, d\theta.</m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\int_0^{\sqrt{2}/2} \int_y^{\sqrt{1-y^2}} \cos(x^2 + y^2) \, dx \, dy.</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The region is the third quadrant portion of the disk centered at the origin of radius 3.
                In rectangular coordinates an equivalent iterated integral is
                <md>
                  \int_{-3}^0 \int_{-\sqrt{9-x^2}}^0 x^2+y^2 \, dy \, dx
                </md>.
                Evaluating the integral in polar coordinates yields
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \int_{0}^{3}  r^3 \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \frac{1}{4}r^4\mid_{0}^{3} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{81}{4} \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{81 \pi}{8}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The region is the disk <m>(x-1)^2+y^2=1</m> centered at <m>(1,0)</m> of radius 1.
                To convert to polar coordinates we substitute for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> to see that
                <md>
                  <mrow>(r \cos(\theta)-1)^2 + (r \sin(\theta))^2 \amp =  1</mrow>
                  <mrow>r^2\cos^2(\theta) -2r\cos(\theta) + 1 + r^2\sin^2(\theta) \amp =  1</mrow>
                  <mrow>r^2 - 2r\cos(\theta) \amp = 0</mrow>
                  <mrow>r \amp = 2\cos(\theta)</mrow>
                </md>.
                So an equivalent iterated integral in polar coordinates is
                <md>
                  \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \int_0^{2 \cos(\theta)} r^2 \, dr \, d\theta
                </md>.
                Evaluating the integral in polar coordinates yields
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \int_{0}^{2\cos(\theta)}  r^2 \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \frac{1}{3}r^3\mid_{0}^{2\cos(\theta)} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \frac{8}{3}\cos^3(\theta) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{8}{3}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \cos(\theta)[1-\sin^2(\theta)] \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{8}{3}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \cos(\theta)-\sin^2(\theta)\cos(\theta) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{8}{3} \left[\sin(\theta)-\frac{1}{3}\sin^3(\theta) \right]\mid_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{8}{3} \left[\left(1-\frac{1}{3} \right) - \left(-1 - \left(-\frac{1}{3}\right) \right)\right]</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{32}{9}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                To convert the equation <m>r = \sin(\theta)</m> to rectangular coordinates,
                we proceed as follows:
                <md>
                  <mrow>r \amp = \sin(\theta)</mrow>
                  <mrow>r^2 \amp = r \sin(\theta)</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2+y^2 \amp = y</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2+y^2-y + \frac{1}{4} \amp = \frac{1}{4}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2 + \left(y-\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 \amp = \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2</mrow>
                </md>.
                So the equation <m>r = \sin(\theta)</m> is the circle centered at the point
                <m>\left( 0, \frac{1}{2}\right)</m> with radius <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                With <m>0 \leq \theta \leq \frac{\pi}{2}</m> we only get the right half of the circle,
                so an equivalent iterated integral in rectangular coordinates is
                <md>
                  \int_0^1 \int_{0}^{\sqrt{y-y^2}} \sqrt{1-(x^2+y^2)} \, dx \, dy
                </md>.
                Evaluating the integral in polar coordinates yields
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_0^{\pi/2} \int_0^{\sin(\theta)} r\sqrt{1-r^2} \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{0}^{\pi/2} -\frac{1}{3} (1-r^2)^{3/2}\mid_{0}^{\sin(\theta)} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \left[(1-\sin^2(\theta))^{3/2}-1 \right] \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \left[(\cos^2(\theta))^{3/2} - 1 \right]  \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \cos^3(\theta) \, d\theta + \frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2} 1  \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \cos(\theta)(1-\sin^2(\theta)) \, d\theta + \frac{\pi}{6}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{6} -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \cos(\theta)- \cos(\theta)\sin^2(\theta) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{6} -\frac{1}{3} \left[ \sin(\theta)- \frac{1}{3}\sin^3(\theta)\right] \mid_{0}^{\pi/2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{6} -\frac{1}{3} \left[ 1- \frac{1}{3}\right]</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{6} -\frac{2}{9}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The graph of <m>x=y</m> is the line through the origin with slope 1 and the graph of
                <m>x = \sqrt{1-y^2}</m> is the top half of the unit circle.
                The circle and the lie <m>x=y</m> intersect at <m>\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)</m>.
                In polar coordinates the unit circle has equation <m>r=1</m> and the line <m>x=y</m> makes and angle of
                <m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m> with the positive <m>x</m>-axis.
                Thus, an equivalent iterated integral in polar coordinates is
                <md>
                  \int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \int_{0}^{1} r \cos(r^2) \, dr \, d\theta
                </md>.
                Evaluating the integral in polar coordinates using the identity for yields
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \int_{0}^{1} r \cos(r^2) \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{\sqrt{2}/2}^{\pi/2} \frac{1}{2} \sin(r^2) \mid_{0}^{1} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}\int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \sin(1)  \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \sin(1) \int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{8} \sin(1)</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The region is the third quadrant portion of the disk centered at the origin of radius 3.
                In rectangular coordinates an equivalent iterated integral is
                <md>
                  \int_{-3}^0 \int_{-\sqrt{9-x^2}}^0 x^2+y^2 \, dy \, dx
                </md>.
                Evaluating the integral in polar coordinates yields
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \int_{0}^{3}  r^3 \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \frac{1}{4}r^4\mid_{0}^{3} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{81}{4} \int_{\pi}^{3\pi/2} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{81 \pi}{8}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The region is the disk <m>(x-1)^2+y^2=1</m> centered at <m>(1,0)</m> of radius 1.
                To convert to polar coordinates we substitute for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> to see that
                <md>
                  <mrow>(r \cos(\theta)-1)^2 + (r \sin(\theta))^2 \amp =  1</mrow>
                  <mrow>r^2\cos^2(\theta) -2r\cos(\theta) + 1 + r^2\sin^2(\theta) \amp =  1</mrow>
                  <mrow>r^2 - 2r\cos(\theta) \amp = 0</mrow>
                  <mrow>r \amp = 2\cos(\theta)</mrow>
                </md>.
                So an equivalent iterated integral in polar coordinates is
                <md>
                  \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \int_0^{2 \cos(\theta)} r^2 \, dr \, d\theta
                </md>.
                Evaluating the integral in polar coordinates yields
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \int_{0}^{2\cos(\theta)}  r^2 \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \frac{1}{3}r^3\mid_{0}^{2\cos(\theta)} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \frac{8}{3}\cos^3(\theta) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{8}{3}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \cos(\theta)[1-\sin^2(\theta)] \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{8}{3}\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \cos(\theta)-\sin^2(\theta)\cos(\theta) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{8}{3} \left[\sin(\theta)-\frac{1}{3}\sin^3(\theta) \right]\mid_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{8}{3} \left[\left(1-\frac{1}{3} \right) - \left(-1 - \left(-\frac{1}{3}\right) \right)\right]</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \frac{32}{9}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                To convert the equation <m>r = \sin(\theta)</m> to rectangular coordinates,
                we proceed as follows:
                <md>
                  <mrow>r \amp = \sin(\theta)</mrow>
                  <mrow>r^2 \amp = r \sin(\theta)</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2+y^2 \amp = y</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2+y^2-y + \frac{1}{4} \amp = \frac{1}{4}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2 + \left(y-\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 \amp = \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2</mrow>
                </md>.
                So the equation <m>r = \sin(\theta)</m> is the circle centered at the point
                <m>\left( 0, \frac{1}{2}\right)</m> with radius <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                With <m>0 \leq \theta \leq \frac{\pi}{2}</m> we only get the right half of the circle,
                so an equivalent iterated integral in rectangular coordinates is
                <md>
                  \int_0^1 \int_{0}^{\sqrt{y-y^2}} \sqrt{1-(x^2+y^2)} \, dx \, dy
                </md>.
                Evaluating the integral in polar coordinates yields
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_0^{\pi/2} \int_0^{\sin(\theta)} r\sqrt{1-r^2} \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{0}^{\pi/2} -\frac{1}{3} (1-r^2)^{3/2}\mid_{0}^{\sin(\theta)} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \left[(1-\sin^2(\theta))^{3/2}-1 \right] \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \left[(\cos^2(\theta))^{3/2} - 1 \right]  \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \cos^3(\theta) \, d\theta + \frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2} 1  \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \cos(\theta)(1-\sin^2(\theta)) \, d\theta + \frac{\pi}{6}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{6} -\frac{1}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/2}  \cos(\theta)- \cos(\theta)\sin^2(\theta) \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{6} -\frac{1}{3} \left[ \sin(\theta)- \frac{1}{3}\sin^3(\theta)\right] \mid_{0}^{\pi/2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{6} -\frac{1}{3} \left[ 1- \frac{1}{3}\right]</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{6} -\frac{2}{9}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The graph of <m>x=y</m> is the line through the origin with slope 1 and the graph of
                <m>x = \sqrt{1-y^2}</m> is the top half of the unit circle.
                The circle and the lie <m>x=y</m> intersect at <m>\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)</m>.
                In polar coordinates the unit circle has equation <m>r=1</m> and the line <m>x=y</m> makes and angle of
                <m>\frac{\pi}{4}</m> with the positive <m>x</m>-axis.
                Thus, an equivalent iterated integral in polar coordinates is
                <md>
                  \int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \int_{0}^{1} r \cos(r^2) \, dr \, d\theta
                </md>.
                Evaluating the integral in polar coordinates using the identity for yields
                <md>
                  <mrow>\int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \int_{0}^{1} r \cos(r^2) \, dr \, d\theta \amp = \int_{\sqrt{2}/2}^{\pi/2} \frac{1}{2} \sin(r^2) \mid_{0}^{1} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}\int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \sin(1)  \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \sin(1) \int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2} \, d\theta</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \frac{\pi}{8} \sin(1)</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        </solution>

        
      </exercise>  
  <exercise xml:id="ez-mult_ints-polar-circle_off_center">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Consider the circle given by <m>x^2 + (y-1)^2 = 1</m> as shown in <xref ref="fig-mult_ints-polar-circle_off_center">Figure</xref>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-mult_ints-polar-circle_off_center">
          <caption>The circle <m>x^2 + (y-1)^2 = 1</m></caption>
          <image width="50%" >
            <description>
              <p>A circle in the <m>xy</m>-plane. The circle passes through the origin and the point <m>(0,2)</m>. The circle is also symmetric about the <m>y</m>-axis.</p>
          </description>
          <sageplot label="img-circyp1">
              var('x,y,t,s')
              plot8=parametric_plot((cos(t),1+sin(t)),(t,0,2*pi),color="black",thickness=3,ticks=[[-1,1],[0,1,2]],axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"])
              plot8                 
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine a polar curve in the form <m>r = f(\theta)</m> that traces out the circle <m>x^2 + (y-1)^2 = 1</m>. To do this, you should substitute <m>x = r \cos(\theta)</m> and <m>y = r \sin(\theta)</m> into the rectangular coordinate equation and solve for <m>r</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>After you substitute, you should expand and combine like terms. You will also want to factor your expression and disregard the <m>r=0</m> solution. </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p>
            The circle <m>C</m> can be described as <m>0 \leq r \leq \ 2\sin(\theta)</m> with <m>0 \leq \theta \leq \pi</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            When expanded, the equation of the circle is <m>x^2+y^2 - 2y = 0</m>. We can write this in polar coordinates as <m>r^2 - 2r \sin(\theta) = 0</m>, or <m>r = 2\sin(\theta)</m>. Thus, the circle <m>C</m> can be described as <m>0 \leq r \leq \ 2\sin(\theta)</m> with <m>0 \leq \theta \leq \pi</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the exact average value of <m>g(x,y) = \sqrt{x^2 + y^2}</m> over the interior of the circle <m>x^2 + (y-1)^2 = 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Use a radially simple description of your region with your result from part a as the upper bound.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m> \frac{32}{9\pi}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The circle <m>C</m> has radius 1, so <m>A(C) = \pi</m>. Note that <m>g(x,y) = \sqrt{x^2 + y^2}</m> can be written in polar form as <m>g(r,\theta) = r</m>. Thus, the average value of <m>g</m> over <m>C</m> is
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{1}{\pi}\int \int_C g(x,y) \, dA \amp = \int_{0}^{\pi} \int_{0}^{2\sin(\theta)} r r \, dr \, d \theta</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{\pi} \frac{r^3}{3} \mid_{0}^{2\sin(\theta)} \, d \theta</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{8}{3\pi} \int_{0}^{\pi} \sin^3(\theta) \, d \theta</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{8}{3\pi} \int_{0}^{\pi} \sin(\theta)(1-\cos^2(\theta)) \, d \theta</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{8}{3\pi} \left(-\cos(\theta)+\frac{\cos^3(\theta)}{3}\right)\mid_{0}^{\pi}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{8}{3\pi}\left(2-\frac{2}{3}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{32}{9\pi}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the volume under the surface <m>h(x,y) = x</m> over the region <m>D</m>, where <m>D</m> is the region bounded above by the line <m>y=x</m> and below by the circle. We have provided a sketch of this as the shaded region in <xref ref="fig-mult_ints-polar-circle_off_center_region">Figure</xref>.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="fig-mult_ints-polar-circle_off_center_region">
            <caption>The region between the circle <m>x^2 + (y-1)^2 = 1</m> and the line <m>y=x</m>.</caption>
            <image width="60%" xml:id="img-F_11_5_Polar_exercise">
              <description>
                <p>
                  A shaded region in the <m>xy</m>-plane. The region is bounded by part of a circle and the portion of the line <m>y=x</m> inside the circle. The circle passes through the origin and the point <m>(0,2)</m>. The circle is also symmetric about the <m>y</m>-axis.
                </p>
            </description><sageplot>
                var('x,y,t,s')
                plot9=parametric_plot((cos(t),1+sin(t)),(t,0,2*pi),color="black",thickness=2,ticks=[[-1,1],[0,1,2]],axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"])
                points=[(2*sin(pi/4*i/25 )*cos(pi/4*i/25), 2*sin(pi/4*i/25)^2) for i in range(26)]
                plot9+=polygon(points,color="lightblue",edgecolor="black",thickness=3)
                plot9                  
              </sageplot>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{1}{6}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            In polar coordinates, the line <m>y=x</m> is represented as <m>r \sin(\theta) = r \cos(\theta)</m>, or <m>\tan(\theta) = 1</m>, or <m>\theta = \frac{\pi}{4}</m>. Therefore, the region <m>D</m> is described by <m>0 \leq r \leq \ 2\sin(\theta)</m> with <m>0 \leq \theta \leq \pi/4</m>. So the under the surface <m>h(x,y) = x</m> over the region <m>D</m> is given by
            <md>
              <mrow>\int \int_D x \, dA \amp = \int_{0}^{\pi/4} \int_{0}^{2\sin(\theta)} r\cos(\theta) r \, dr \, d \theta</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \int_{0}^{\pi/4} \cos(\theta) \frac{r^3}{3} \mid_{0}^{2\sin(\theta)} \, d \theta</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{8}{3} \int_{0}^{\pi/4} \cos(\theta) \sin^3(\theta) \, d \theta</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{8}{12} \sin^4(\theta) \mid_{0}^{\pi/4}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{3} \left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)^4</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{6}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>  
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain why in both of the previous parts it is advantageous to use polar coordinates.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            In (b), it is very difficult to integrate <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</m> in rectangular coordinates, and in (c) the region <m>D</m> is much more easily described in polar coordinates.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            In (b), it is very difficult to integrate <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</m> in rectangular coordinates, and in (c) the region <m>D</m> is much more easily described in polar coordinates.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </exercise>


    



